'''Mohannad al-Masri''' (born 1981),<ref name='ottawa'>{{cite news |title=War on the Islamic State – Russian forces expanding airport in Syria in preparation for new military base |first=David |last=Pugliese |url= http://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/war-on-the-islamic-state-russian-forces-expanding-airport-in-syria-in-preparation-for-new-military-base |newspaper=''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' |date=13 September 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref><ref name='chicago'>{{cite news |title=Syria group: Russia expanding major Syrian airport |first=Sarah |last=El Deeb |url= http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/sns-bc-ml--syria-20150913-story.html |newspaper=''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref><ref name='japan'>{{cite news |title=Russia expanding major Syrian airport, monitor reports |first= |last= |url= http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/09/14/world/russia-expanding-major-syrian-airport-monitor-reports/ |newspaper=''[[The Japan Times]]'' |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> known by the [[Pseudonym|alias]] '''Abu Yahia al-Hamawi''',<ref name='ottawa' /><ref name='chicago' /><ref name='japan' /> (sometimes transliterated '''Abu Yahya al-Hamawi'''<ref name='ctvnews'>{{cite news |title=Syrian militant group gaining influence after rebranding as moderate option |first=Bassem |last=Mroue |url= http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/syrian-militant-group-gaining-influence-after-rebranding-as-moderate-option-1.2600600 |newspaper=[[CTV News]] |date=8 October 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref><ref name='reuters'>{{cite news |title=Resilient insurgent group Ahrar al-Sham to play bigger role in Syria |first=Mariam |last=Karouny |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-syria-crisis-ahrar-insight-idUSKCN0RM0EZ20150922 |newspaper=[[Reuters]] |date=22 September 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref><ref name='toronto'>{{cite news |title=Syrian rebels carry out reign of terror in north: Amnesty |first=Olivia |last=Ward |url= https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2016/07/05/syrian-rebels-carry-out-reign-of-terror-in-north-amnesty.html |newspaper=''[[Toronto Star]]'' |date=5 July 2016 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref><ref name='monitor'>{{cite news |title=Davutoglu proposes refugee 'container city' |first=Fehim |last=Tastekin |url= http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2015/09/turkey-syria-assad-boutique-state-refugees-container-state.html |newspaper=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=30 September 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> or '''Abu Yehya al-Hamawi'''<ref name='war'>{{cite news |title=Ahrar Al-Sham's Revisionist Jihadism |first=Sam |last=Heller |url= https://warontherocks.com/2015/09/ahrar-al-shams-revisionist-jihadism/ |newspaper=War on the Rocks |date=30 September 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref>) was the third leader of the [[Salafi movement|Salafist]] [[Ahrar al-Sham]] during the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=Lund_blog/> He served from 12 September 2015<ref name='war' /><ref>[https://twitter.com/aron_ld/status/642721159335800832 Aron Lund on Twitter]</ref> until his term ended in November 2016.
==Biography==
Al-Hamawi came from [[Qalaat al-Madiq]], [[Hama Governorate|Hama]], [[Syria]]. He trained as a [[civil engineer]] and studied at [[Tishreen University]] in [[Latakia]].<ref name='ottawa' /><ref name='chicago' /><ref name='japan' /><ref name='reuters' /> He was with [[Hadi Al Abdullah]] who was a journalist during the civil war. He was an [[Activism|activist]] and an [[Prisoner|inmate]] of the "[[Islamism|Islamist]] wing" of the Syrian government’s main political prison in [[Sednaya Prison|Sednaya]] from 2007 to 2011. An article in the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' described him as a "[[political prisoner]]".<ref name='toronto' /> He was released in 2011, when the [[Civil uprising phase of the Syrian Civil War|Syrian uprising]] began.<ref name='ottawa' /><ref name='chicago' /><ref name='japan' />
He later became leader of the Osama bin Zeid Company, a [[militia]] based around his hometown of Qalaat al-Madiq, and then rose through the ranks to become leader of Ahrar al-Sham in September 2015.<ref name=Lund_blog>{{cite web |url=http://www.joshualandis.com/blog/abu-yahia-al-hamawi-ahrar-al-shams-new-leader/ |title=Abu Yahia al-Hamawi, Ahrar al-Sham’s New Leader |first=Aron |last=Lund |work=Syria Comment |date=12 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref> According to ''[[Al-Monitor]]'', the change is leadership is said to have made Ahrar Al-Sham "more palatable to [[Western world|the West]]" since al-Hamawi "is seen as someone who will fit the 'moderate Salafist' image Ahrar al-Sham wants to have".<ref name='monitor' /> According to ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', al-Hamawi claimed that "Ahrar al-Sham was [[mainstream]] and aligned with Western interests."<ref name='dailybeast'>{{cite news |title=In the Syrian Ceasefire Shell Game, the Good Guys May Be Bad Guys |first=Alexander |last=Decina |url= http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/03/01/in-the-syrian-ceasefire-shell-game-the-good-guys-may-be-bad-guys.html |newspaper=''[[The Daily Beast]]'' |date=1 March 2016 |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> In December 2015, al-Hamawi sent Labib al-Nahhas to [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]] in order to participate in the Saudi-led rebel conference that produced the [[High Negotiations Committee]] (HNC).<ref name='dailybeast' /> Al-Hamawi has also falsely claimed that [[Al-Nusra Front|Al-Nusra]] had withdrawn from the [[Army of Conquest]].<ref name='dailybeast' />
His term as leader could have been extended,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sources to Qasioun: Ahrar Alsham movement looking for new leader |url= https://www.qasioun.net/en/news/show/42006/Sources_to_Qasioun_Ahrar_Alsham_movement_looking_for_new_leader |newspaper=Qasioun News |date=10 November 2016 |accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> but the Shura Council of Ahrar al-Sham appointed [[Ali al-Omar]] as leader in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: Turkey says 2 soldiers missing in Syria |first=Sarah |last=El Deeb |url= https://apnews.com/8b5584705c6840af95342a92aa5c70fa |newspaper=AP |date=30 November 2016 |accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>
